<i>yate</i> + <i>man</i>. Compare   Yates  ."]},{"name":"Gates","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Gate</b> with plural or excrescent <i>-s</i>. The English surname <i>Gate</i> has three possible origins: (i) a topographic name from Middle English <i>gate</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>geat</i>, dative plural <i>gatum</i>), denoting someone who lived by a gate or set of gates (possibly sometimes an occupational name for a gate keeper; compre Yates); (ii) in northern England, the East Midlands, and East Anglia, a topographic name from Middle English <i>gate</i> ‘street, road, path’ (Old Norse <i>gata</i>) for someone who lived by a road (compare   Street  ); (iii) a nickname meaning ‘goat’, from northern Middle English <i>gate</i>, <i>gait</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i>, Old Norse <i>geitr</i>).","Americanized form of German <b>Götz</b> (see   Goetz  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French <b>Barrière</b> (see   Barriere  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":27,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Yates was born about 1310, in Dursley, Gloucestershire, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Robert Yate."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1335":"umbes 1335","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Dursley, Gloucestershire, England":"Dursley, Gloucestershire, England","Arlingham, Gloucestershire, England":"Arlingham, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1335":"noin 1335","about 1310":"noin 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Dursley, Gloucestershire, England":"Dursley, Gloucestershire, England","Arlingham, Gloucestershire, England":"Arlingham, Gloucestershire, Eng